			<td>986</td><td>AWS</td><td>Arctic Weather Satellite</td><td>ESA, EUMETSAT</td><td>Commissioning</td><td>16 Aug 2024</td><td>Aug 2029</td><td>AWS is the protoflight satellite for a planned constellation of meteorological microsatellites providing passive microwave soundings for global atmospheric temperature and humidity profiles soundings in all weather conditions, with frequent revisits over the Arctic and Antarctic polar regions. This constellation (called EPS-Sterna, which is named after the latin name Sterna for the Arctic Tern) will consist of 3 orbital planes with 2 satellites in each orbital plane. With a nominal satellite lifetime of 5 years, a first launch in 2029 and 2 replenishments of each orbit plane, a minimum mission lifetime for the full system of 13 years will be achieved. Local Solar time for AWS is 09:00 - 11:00 and  EPS-Sterna Descending LST is  03:30, 07:30, 11:30.</td><td>AWS Instrument</td><td>1959</td><td>Sun-synchronous</td><td>595 km</td><td>97 mins</td><td>97.79 deg</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>Ascending</td><td>https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Meteorological_missions/Arctic_Weather_Satellite</td><td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr><tr>
			<td>768</td><td>Biomass</td><td>Biomass</td><td>ESA</td><td>Commissioning</td><td>29 Apr 2025</td><td>Oct 2030</td><td>Biomass will provide global maps of forest biomass and height (at 200 m resolution) and forest disturbance (at 50 m resolution) every 6 months. This information will lead to a better understanding of the state of Earth’s forests, how they are changing over time, and advance our knowledge of the carbon cycle.</td><td>P-Band SAR</td><td>1722</td><td>Sun-synchronous</td><td>666 km</td><td>102.6 mins</td><td>98 deg</td><td>3</td><td>06:00</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>Ascending</td><td>https://earth.esa.int/eogateway/missions/biomass</td><td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr><tr>
